But when we corneto inquire into the specific charges laid by Strabo against Pytheas it is surprising how little we can find to justify all this censure. One mis- statement which he brings home to him is that the length oi Britain was more than ao,ooo stades, or a,5oo Roman miles, whichis certainly an enormous exaggeration. Another is that Kent was several days' sail from Gaul (p. 63). This Pytheas might very well have said in good saith, having noted the time it took himself to get from the one coast to the other. We do not know from what point he deserted the coast of Gaul and made across to Britain.
